segments.text: 25th, 1975, with interviewer Mike Stevens, at home Mrs. C.O.
Powell on 409 Barton Street in Hearn.
Is that on there?
Yeah, I want that on there for a reason, just for my own reference.
Now do I start?
Yeah.
Why don't you start out, like I said, tell us something about your family or whatever.
My grandparents came from Frankfurt, Germany in 1860.
why they chose to come to the United States.
Times was getting hard there.
And they came to, let me see, I think they came to New Orleans.
I think that, I've heard my mother say that.
And she was born 1863.
And then she and my daddy married
And I was born in Rutherford County, Tennessee in 18 and 92.
How many was in your family?
How many brother and sister do you have?
With me?
Yeah.
I had one sister and two brothers.
And my mother died in 19 and 10.
And I was in college in Murfreesboro, Tennessee at Teachers College.
when my mother died.
And then I went to college, and then in 19, I went two years.
In 19 and 13, my husband and I married.
And we had eight children, and we educated all of them.
And then we came in 19,
In 29, Daddy got transferred from the Southern Pacific Railroad, I mean, no, no, from the L&N Railroad to the Southern Pacific Hill.
And he worked for the Southern Pacific until he died in 1970.
And during the War II, I had two boys in the service.
One of them, he worked for the railroad, was Navy CB.
And the other one had just finished high school.
And we had to sign for him.
My daddy did.
I wouldn't sign for him.
And he joined up with that bunch from Harris County and Waller County to take revenge on Pearl Harbor.
Go ahead.
Go ahead.
I'm just checking this thing.
OK, it's doing fine.
And they sunk that ship at Pearl Harbor and there was a thousand left Houston.
And so you've been, how long have you been here in Hearn now?
And I have been in Hearn off and on ever since 34.
Why I say off and on, if the company, if the railroad wanted to send my husband anywhere,
Well, we'd just pack up and go wherever they'd send him, and then when he got through that job, we'd come back to Hearn, and he'd go back to the job here.
Who were some of the places you went off and on?
Oh, my goodness.
I've been up and down the railroad from Sherman to Cypress, Texas.
We have lived in Sherman.
We have lived in Kaufman.
I've lived in Ennis.
I've lived in Dallas.
You've made the rounds, Ann.
And Cypress.
And then, of course, here.
We've always called her.
And ever since 34, we've always called her in our home.
Home base.
Well, this is where we come back to.
And then I have my baby boy has three degrees.
He got his BS degree from Sam Houston.
And then he was principal of a school at Saratoga, Texas, a year.
Where is that?
Oh, out here somewhere.
Oh, it's out from, well, I know how to get there, but it's between Liberty and back towards Humboldt in there.
And then he went back then to Sam Houston and got his master degree.
And we've just always, Daddy, my husband, was born in Cook County, Texas.
And when his mother and daddy, he had two brothers, and they was great big boys, and they decided they'd go back to Tennessee.
And Daddy, of course, was big enough that he had that Texas fever.
He always wanted to come back to Texas.
And of course we've always been satisfied here because there's so many advantages here that we didn't have there.
Understand I am a Tennessee fan.
I was born in red there.
But I've never regretted coming to Texas.
What do you think some of the advantages of living here are?
A whole lot of the advantages until the Depression, until this Depression came on, was work.
There's so many more kinds of work here than there was back then.
You mean there was more work here than there was in Tennessee?
Yes, because there was more, you know, different kinds of work.
And then we was living in Grosbeck when the other Depression was.
Which one are you talking about now?
You know, the depression, it started in 29, and it really got bad in 30 and 31.
And of course, we had plenty to eat and everything because Daddy was on a salary.
But when everybody around you is out of work, well, it makes times hard on everybody, just like it is now.
And money was tight.
And they talk about the Depression then.
Well, hard times is worse now than they were then.
You really think so?
Yes, sir.
I think so.
And I'll tell you why.
There is so many more people.
The population is greater.
And then there is so many things to do, so many things that shut down.
Way back then, well, there wasn't so many factories and all these
You take Deer Park, Lake Jackson, and Lake City, and Texas City, and all those.
They wasn't on a boom then.
And now, well, the population is so great.
And everything is so high.
Things didn't go out of proportion in the other depression, but it is in this one.
You see what makes it.
Now, I am on.

a railroad retirement i draw a check and i you can go in a grocery store and something's jumped way up this week well i get my check i don't get any increase in my salary it's the same amount it's just still the same amount but i have got to try to meet that high price and i can't do it
I cannot do it.
That's a problem for everybody.
Everybody.
That's it.
The claim is now there's just no money.
The people's got no money.
And what little they have got, they've had to spend it because everything was so high.
Do you remember anything?
Any specific incident that was really tough on you during the Depression that you had to deal with, say, about a thing being so tight or whatever?
Any specific thing that you can think of that was really bad?
Well, I can tell you one thing, if this would be interesting.
My husband worked for the railroad, and he worked 15 men.
And in those days,
the company furnished your house and had some little houses in the yard for these men.
And he had to figure out that 15 men that they worked three days a week.
Of course, Daddy drew his salary just the same.
But these men and one man had a wife and 11 children.
11 kids?
11 kids on three days a week.
Talk about a thing being tied.
And every morning, I'd fix up a big pan of beans, some kind of dried beans, a big pan of meal, and a great big chunk of side meat.
Then meat didn't come wrapped up in little squares like it did now.
It was just the whole side of a hog.
And I'd send one of my boys out to her house in the yard.
I done that for over a year.
to keep from them children from going hungry.
And that's the way they lived.
That's a perfect example of what I wanted.
Yeah.
And now I look at tuition.
When we took this grandson that I am educating, we took him, I brought him from the hospital in a bassinet.
You're talking about John?
What are you talking about?
And then when Karen was five years old, I took her.
Okay, just a second.
Let me stop you here.
Why don't you back up?
I mean, I know who you're talking about, obviously, but go ahead and say who you're talking about for the tape.
Say who you're talking about.
I'm talking about my grandchildren, my two of my grandchildren.
Well, we raised both of them.
And if I live till the ninth day of May, John will graduate from A&M.
Karen has got one more year in high school.
It has been hard since the time she's got like the hell.
But I am a great believer in the Lord.
I believe if you live right and do right, God's going to take care of you.
It may be in a mysterious way, but I think that he's going to take care of you.
There has been times since Daddy died that I'd think, well, how in the world am I going to do?
And about the time when I would start to worry, which I shouldn't worry, because it's a sin to worry about something that's beyond your control.
I'd get a check from some of my children.
Really?
And then that'd solve your problem, right?
And that solves it.
I have never been hungry for the want of something to eat.
I've always had a way to get about.
I've had a good place to stay.
John and Karen's always had plenty of clothes to wear.
And a way to get about.
They've never been hungry.
And then I don't know whether we've had hard times or not.
Just depending on what you consider hard times, I guess.
Well, it's been hard.
But God didn't promise me no bed of roses.
Yeah, that's true.
No, that's right.
That's the way it is.
But I can tell you what.
If you look about, you'll always find somebody that's in a worse shape than you are, financially, health, or anything.
I have been sick a lot.
The 16th of June, I will be 83 years old.
That's pretty old.
And I can get about.
I get out here in my yard.
I do every lick of work.
I don't run over nothing.
I don't keep house anymore like I used to.
But people get in and out.
I sing a lot sometimes.
And sometimes I get ashamed of myself that I think, well,
Why do I want to complain?
I've got everything that God has promised to give me.
And you see children, there's children in this town that's hungry.
And another thing, that in the last 20 years, there's been so much crying, so much going on.
When I grew up,
Oh, me.
If you heard of a killing, the neighbors gathered at one another's house, and that was something terrible.
And now you pick up the newspaper, and this one killed that one, and that one, and you lay the paper down and don't think nothing about it.
And if there was any dope or anything like that, I never heard of it.
Compared to now when it's a typical thing.
When it's just a typical thing now that...
Oh, I think they're on dope.
They must be on dope, just as unconcerned if I'd walk in my kitchen and take a drink of water.
Why don't you tell us some of the things maybe about, I like what you're talking about now, how things maybe have changed since the time you were a teenager.
of them to now.
Oh, my gracious.
Just a few things you can think of, maybe even a way, you know.
Well, starting out, what was Hearn like when you first came here?
What?
What was Hearn like when you first came here?
Well, my baby girl is 42 years old, and she graduated in Hearn.
And she thinks it is terrible the way the teenagers do now and the way she done.
They didn't get in no car and ride and all over town.
And people, everybody, we had a car.
Of course, gas wasn't high.
How high was it?
Well, the best I remember is about 18 or 20 cents a gallon.
And that wasn't high for that time?
Oh, no.
And the first automobile that we bought was
19 and 15, I guess.
And we give $540 for it.
$540 for a car?
For a car, Ford.
Was it a real nice car?
Yes, certainly was nice.
$540 compared to now, $4,000.
What there are now, yeah.
And you could buy a set of furniture.
a bedroom suit for $50.
Goodness.
And when is this now?
What year are you talking about now?
Well, now, with the furniture, oh, I expect it was about 19.
Well, 19 and 23, I bought a bedroom suit.
I got a dresser.
They didn't have Chester drawers then.
They called them washstands.
And a bed and a mattress and a rocking chair for $54.
And I guess I'd grown them maybe then.
Maybe I thought that was too high.
Compared to what it is now.
Yeah.
Well, you see, what we got then, when we came to Texas, Daddy

got 65 a month we had more money then than we did when he retired in 63 and he was making over 400 and they kept up our house we didn't have any expenses on our utilities and telephone bill yeah i mean you had more money back yes sir we did we could i have seen the time
when we would buy our groceries to last a month.
And it would be about $25.
For the whole month?
Yes, sir.
Maybe we'd have to buy bread or something, or maybe milk, some little item.
And now you can't get by $25 a week.
I can go to the grocery store now and just a few items and be $10 or $12 and come out swinging the sack.
And put it in your glove compartment almost.
Yes, that's right.
Well, how has Hearn changed from the time you came here?
Well, the biggest change in Hearn is the morality.
The what?
Morality.
People has lost their honesty and morality.
You mean at the heck when you were here?
Yes, sir.
When in the happenings of today, if it had happened back, well, I'll say back in 30, people would have thought it was something terrible.
You mean like he's killing some things?
Yes.
And now it's killings and stealings and robbery.
People don't think.
If anything back then had happened like that it happens now, why, the families, nobody wouldn't have seen them for a year, for they'd have felt so disgraced.
And now, why, they just laugh about it and go on.
Can you remember any of the older buildings or structures that were around then that are gone now?
You know, some of the, maybe a grocery store or something like this?
Oh, my goodness, yes.
I think this would be kind of interesting.
Well, again, that's the post office.
The post office used to be on the corner of, that's 4th Street, isn't it, that runs across the track?
Well, right there where Gibson was, that's where old post office used to be.
Really?

only that was an old shackled building like and then they built a new post office and then on down from the post office there on the corner from the post office coming back towards the Pamela's sister back towards his office there was a grocery store there on the corner Italian had it I've done even forgot his name
And then there was a shoe shop then, right next to that grocery store.
And then across where the First State Bank is, there was about two doors up, there was the grocery store.
All of that is gone.
That's gone completely now.
And where that Western Auto is, there used to be a coffee shop there.
And let me see.
Where was the?
What used to be?
Always nothing hardly that where things is now.
There's something else.
Now the main cafe.
That's been main cafe.
A long time in the city cafe.
Course the main.
Well, it hadn't changed hands too much, but the city cafe has been run by Pammises ever since, Lord, I don't know hardly what year.
But it's been a long, long time.
It's been in their family.
Of course, Helen Pammis, her husband, Mr. Tom, they was the last ones that had it.
Bill Pammers, his mother and daddy had the City Cafe first.
Then his daddy died, and then she kept it on a while, and then Mr. Tom and Helen took it.

Say back, I don't know, say back in a

And now you just drive along and you see College Station, City Limits College Station.
All that new building over on that side where Sears begins, and there, all that's been put up there.
And Montgomery and Ward used to have a store
I don't remember what street it was now.
And it burnt.
And they built.
Do you remember when this was?
No, I don't remember what year it was.
That's my trouble.
I can't remember the years.
I used to could remember the year of anything, but now I have to go to my record to even see when my kids was born.
Well, do you remember anything in Bryan that used to be there and still is?
You know, something that was around, say, in about the 30s and 40s and still maybe been remodeled or something now.
I don't know where it would be down unless it'd be something downtown.
And A&M College used to just be agriculture and engineering, mechanical engineering.
And the railroad, there used to be trains, of course.
We had trains then.
And they would stop.
at A&M at the depot there, and A&M boys would get on there.
And I can go, I believe I can now go to the old part of the college.
Where is it?
I don't guess I even know where it is.
Well, the old, I don't know, I have never asked John.
I wonder if they still have classes there or anything.
Like, you know where the railroad track runs, don't you?
Yeah.
Well, over on this side, you could see Kyle Field out from there.
And here then, and the agriculture part was over here.
Is it still that way, still across the track?
Yeah, yeah.
I know what you're talking about, out by the veterinary medicine.
Well, what now is the College of Veterinary Medicine?
Yeah.
Well, it's still across the track, though, huh?
Well, that was very small.
outfit but that was separate from over here.
How large was A&M back during those times?
Oh my goodness.
Did you have any idea how many people around or anything?

I just I wish that I could see Milton McNair his boys went there and of course now they are their granddaddies now they graduated from there but I just I'd be afraid to say but what did it what did it look like then what did they uh
structure and the buildings and things looked like that.
Well, there were concrete buildings over on this side and some of them on that side.
And those buildings are still there.
And they were gray, kind of rusty looking, but everybody was proud of A&M.
And then the way, I think so many times, Sunday evening when we carried John,
It was right funny.
There were so few cars, they were just beginning to come in, the boys and girls coming in from the spring break.
And then there were all the dormitories and everything in the world, just one building after another, and then still a building.

just go ahead and keep talking that's right i'm just trying to it will be a and m someday and it won't be long it'll be one of the biggest colleges there is yeah i think i heard somewhere it was one about the second or third largest growth had been made well it it will be because the way it's a growing and then you see any field you want to get into you can get into it at a m you don't have to go a little bit here and run all kind of
And then I believe in less than five years' time, premed and law anyway, and science, that you can go ahead and finish there.
You think they'll have a law and a medical school there?
Yeah, I sure do.
They'll have medicine before they wear a law, I believe.
I don't know.
But that's just my guess about it.
You were talking about the connection you and your husband and family and things they've had with the railroad.
Do you remember anything at, did you ever have anything with the Milliken Railroad?
With what?
With the railroad and activity down around Milliken?
No.
They had, there'd been lots of wrecks, bad wrecks, but they had one terrible wreck at Cypress one time.

uh train got off the track and uh they uh let me see what was it i don't know some kind of chemical and that caught a fire and one of the engineers burnt to death really was that the uh during these times say again about the 30s or maybe even 20 years or so was that the main way of traveling by train especially long distance traveling even if you took if you had

Yeah.
They're families.
We'd have a family pass.
And then, of course, Daddy always had a separate pass because he'd be called to go somewhere, and he had to have that pass right then.
And we'd ride trains.
We didn't go anywhere in a car, and we've always had a car.
But we'd be foolish to go in a car when there we had a pass to go from here to.
